The paper deals with algorithms for drawing random samples from a large data stream, which is a classic problem in data structures and algorithms. The fact that the input elements are distributed across multiple sites and communicate via a central coordinator suggests that the paper may belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The mention of heavy hitters also suggests that the paper may belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The use of randomness and probability in the algorithm suggests that the paper may belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Finally, the mention of computation and messages sent in the system suggests that the paper may belong to the Databases (cs.DB) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories.
